<p><b>Gil Scott-Heron</b> (born <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1949-04-01"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="04-01"><a href="/wiki/April_1" title="April 1">April 1</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1949" title="1949">1949</a></span>) is an <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> <a href="/wiki/Poet" title="Poet">poet</a>, <a href="/wiki/Musician" title="Musician">musician</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Author" title="Author">author</a> known primarily for his late 1960s and early 1970s work as a <a href="/wiki/Spoken_word_soul" title="Spoken word soul">spoken word soul</a> performer and his collaborative work with musician <a href="/wiki/Brian_Jackson_(musician)" title="Brian Jackson (musician)">Brian Jackson</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Famous_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Famous-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> His collaborative efforts with Jackson featured a musical fusion of jazz, blues and soul music, as well as lyrical content concerning social and political issues of the time, delivered in both <a href="/wiki/Rapping" title="Rapping">rapping</a> and <a href="/wiki/Melismatic" title="Melismatic" class="mw-redirect">melismatic</a> vocal styles by Scott-Heron. The music of these albums, most notably <i><a href="/wiki/Pieces_of_a_Man" title="Pieces of a Man">Pieces of a Man</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Winter_in_America" title="Winter in America">Winter in America</a></i> in the early 1970s, influenced and helped engender later African-American music genres such as <a href="/wiki/Hip_hop_music" title="Hip hop music">hip hop</a> and <a href="/wiki/Neo_soul" title="Neo soul">neo soul</a>. Scott-Heron's recording work is often associated with <a href="/wiki/Black_power" title="Black power" class="mw-redirect">black militant</a> activism and has received much critical acclaim for one of his most well-known compositions "<a href="/wiki/The_Revolution_Will_Not_Be_Televised" title="The Revolution Will Not Be Televised">The Revolution Will Not Be Televised</a>". On his influence, a music writer later noted that "Scott-Heron's unique proto-rap style influenced a generation of hip-hop artists".<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
